			<td class="kcol-first kcol-ktopicicon">
				<img src="https://sesa.org.au/components/com_kunena/template/default/images/topicicons/icon_normal.png" alt="emo" />			</td>

			<td class="kcol-mid ktopictittle">
							<div class="ktopic-title-cover">
					<a class="ktopic-title km" href="/index.php?option=com_kunena&amp;func=view&amp;catid=14&amp;id=32&amp;Itemid=85" title="This is a reply to Hervé's post above on behalf of Robert Halligan
----------------------------------------------------------------------

From: Robert Halligan 
Sent: Wednesday, 13 April 2011 9:17 PM

Hello Hervé

Apologies, I need to respond here for reasons of time and lack of internet access while flying. If time permits, I will repeat my response on the SESA website on-line forum.

I am not sure that the proposal needs a Working Party of SESA ex presidents, but if there is a majority view that it does, I would be happy to contribute. I do, however, agree that the proposal needs to be decided upon in a way which involves substantial member participation. A vote by those attending the impending AGM is a bit marginal in this respect. A postal vote or on-line vote of members might be preferable, with the ballot info presenting a For and Against case (if there is an Against case). 

Disposition of SESA funds seems to me to be an entirely separate issue that should be decided upon by the SESA Committee (that is why they are elected).

The only country in which multiple INCOSE chapters seems to work is the United States. It certainly hasn’t worked in Turkey (which has chapters in Istanbul and Ankara). By contrast, nationally based chapters with regional branches is working extremely well in the United Kingdom and South Africa.

We have an elected Committee. I am comfortable that they have decided that two options should be put to the vote (maintain the status quo and become an INCOSE chapter). I will be comfortable with either of the possible results from a vote that has involved substantial member participation in the process.

Cheers
Robert" rel="follow">Re: SETE2011 AGM &amp; Proposed Merger of SESA &amp; INCOSE</a>				</div>
				<div style="display:none">This is a reply to Hervé's post above on behalf of Robert Halligan<br />
----------------------------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
From: Robert Halligan <br />
Sent: Wednesday, 13 April 2011 9:17 PM<br />
<br />
Hello Hervé<br />
<br />
Apologies, I need to respond here for reasons of time and lack of internet access while flying. If time permits, I will repeat my response on the SESA website on-line forum.<br />
<br />
I am not sure that the proposal needs a Working Party of SESA ex presidents, but if there is a majority view that it does, I would be happy to contribute. I do, however, agree that the proposal needs to be decided upon in a way which involves substantial member participation. A vote by those attending the impending AGM is a bit marginal in this respect. A postal vote or on-line vote of members might be preferable, with the ballot info presenting a For and Against case (if there is an Against case). <br />
<br />
Disposition of SESA funds seems to me to be an entirely separate issue that should be decided upon by the SESA Committee (that is why they are elected).<br />
<br />
The only country in which multiple INCOSE chapters seems to work is the United States. It certainly hasn’t worked in Turkey (which has chapters in Istanbul and Ankara). By contrast, nationally based chapters with regional branches is working extremely well in the United Kingdom and South Africa.<br />
<br />
We have an elected Committee. I am comfortable that they have decided that two options should be put to the vote (maintain the status quo and become an INCOSE chapter). I will be comfortable with either of the possible results from a vote that has involved substantial member participation in the process.<br />
<br />
Cheers<br />
Robert</div>
