				<tr class="krow1">
			<td class="kcol-first kcol-ktopicicon">
				<img src="https://sesa.org.au/components/com_kunena/template/default/images/topicicons/icon_normal.png" alt="emo" />			</td>

			<td class="kcol-mid ktopictittle">
							<div class="ktopic-title-cover">
					<a class="ktopic-title km" href="/index.php?option=com_kunena&amp;func=view&amp;catid=14&amp;id=31&amp;Itemid=85" title="Hi everyone,

I'm adding this post on behalf of Hervé Rochecouste - please look for a follow up response to this from Robert Halligan. Hervé &amp; Robert are past Presidents of SESA.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------
On 12/04/11 9:22 PM, &quot;Herve Rochecouste&quot; wrote:

Hello everyone again,
 
After reading Paul Miller’s advice about commenting on the web site I have decided to send a last message on this forum about the SESA/INCOSE AGM proposal. I have also received a few comments directly send to my email, a few phone calls, and also a few direct comments from colleagues in current projects. After my longer previous comment I will summarise as follows:
 

1. As Systems Engineers we are trained to address critical issues by the proposal and analysis of several options, trading offs positives v/s negatives etc, then use all that to formulate the best agreement and decision. In this particular case we appear to have by-passed everything and propose a solution directly for adoption in a meeting that around 30% of the membership base attends, and probably in a short time after all the other usual important AGM proceedings are out of the way. This is much too important to be given such a dismissive treatment – we can put out technical knowledge to good use and adopt a more inclusive process.

2. I therefore propose that the best course of action is to request that Paul Logan removes the current motion from the agenda to open options for more complete analyses and deliberations. I suggest that such an important needs to have its own agenda in a later Extraordinary AGM to be held in 6 months time (e.g., Late Oct or Nov 2011). 

3. In the mean time I suggest that we form an effective Working Party of all the SESA ex presidents and the current one to work on this, i.e., look at the best options for a way forward, use the Newsletter/Forum to communicate options and eventually promote the best one for consideration via an inclusive postal (or e-postal) referendum. The Extraordinary AGM will then be the ratification vehicle for the option accepted by the majority. 

4. We can discuss the process to be adopted (only) and this coming AGM, and if what I am proposing above is agreeable, I volunteer to lead that Working Party of Presidents to deliver something in Oct/Nov 2011. I have successfully led the group that formed SESA in 1993/94, worked in the NCOSE committee as Director when we were establishing INCOSE as an international body, led the first INCOSE International Symposium (as Chair) in Australia in 2001, and also worked with South African &amp; European colleagues to establish INCOSE Chapters in their respective regions. In all those cases we were successful and delivered the best option at the time after careful consideration of several others. I therefore also think that I can lead this initiative to the optimal conclusion, and with consensus. 

5. I am not sure whether all the “old timers” are still on this forum list, but I kindly ask Robert Halligan, Professor Stephen Cook, Roger McCowan, Michael Lonsdale, Pat Lockley, Kerry-Jan Lunney (did I forget anyone?) and the current president + committee to support what I am proposing here. 

6. In addition, other SESA members on this forum who feel they want to support this alternate course of action should follow Paul Miller’s instruction and provide their views, and hopefully approval on the website on-line forum. 

I am sorry if I upset anyone, but my only motivation is to ensure that the membership base gets the best deal possible, and this will surely flow down to continue the improvement of the Systems Engineering practice in Australia. I personally believe that the move to a number of INCOSE chapters in Australia (maybe 3) is timely (not possible when we formed SESA, and too expensive or difficult in the following years), but I think that we should not do this hastily. We have a duty to provide an opportunity for at least 80% of the membership base to participate.

Hervé" rel="follow">Re: SETE2011 AGM &amp; Proposed Merger of SESA &amp; INCOSE</a>				</div>
